{"cursor":"11910","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n (1855)]] circa. 1514]]\n\n'Arion' () was a kitharode in ancient Greece, a Dionysiac poet credited with\ninventing the dithyramb: \"As a literary composition for chorus dithyramb was the\ncreation of Arion of Corinth,\" Pickard-Cambridge, Sir Arthur Wallace. 1927.\nDithyramb Tragedy and Comedy. Second edition revised by T.B.L. Webster, 1962.\nOxford: Oxford University Press, 1997. ISBN 0-19-814227-7. The islanders\nof Lesbos claimed him as their native son, but Arion found a patron in\nPeriander, tyrant of Corinth. Although notable for his musical inventions, Arion\nis chiefly remembered for the fantastic myth of his kidnapping by pirates and\nmiraculous rescue by dolphins, a folktale motif. The dolphin's love of music\nand of humans was proverbial among Greeks (Euripides, [[Electra\n(Euripides)|Electra]] 435f; for the folktale motif, see Stith Thompson, Motif\nIndex of Folk Literature (Bloomington IN) 1955-58) s.v. B300-B349, and B473,\nB767. Herodotus (1,23) says \"Arion was second to none of the lyre-players\nin his time and was also the first man we know of to compose and name the\ndithyramb and teach it in Corinth\". However J.H. Sleeman observes of the\ndithyramb, or circular chorus, \"It is first mentioned by Archilochus (c 665 BC)â¦\nArion flourished at least 50 years laterâ¦ probably gave it a more artistic form,\nadding a chorus of 50 people, personating satyrsâ¦ who danced around an altar of\nDionysus. He was doubtless the first to introduce the dithyramb into\nCorinth\". J.H. Sleeman, ed. Herodotus Book I.\n\nArion is also associated with the origins of tragedy: of Solon John the Deacon\nreports: âArion of Methymna first introduced the drama [i.e. action] of tragedy,\nas Solon indicated in his poem entitled Elegies\". Solon, Fragment 30a W,\nnoted in Eric Csapo and Margaret Christina Miller, The Origins of Theater in\nAncient Greece and beyond: from ritual to drama, 2007 \"Pre-Aristotelian\nfragments\", p. 10.\n","linknr":256,"url":"Arion","recorded":1374522703,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Arion&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Arion&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Arion_(disambiguation)","/wiki/File:William-Adolphe_Bouguereau_(1825-1905)_-_Arion_on_a_Sea_Horse_(1855).jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/25/William-Adolphe_Bouguereau_%281825-1905%29_-_Arion_on_a_Sea_Horse_%281855%29.jpg/240px-William-Adolphe_Bouguereau_%281825-1905%29_-_Arion_on_a_Sea_Horse_%281855%29.jpg","/wiki/File:William-Adolphe_Bouguereau_(1825-1905)_-_Arion_on_a_Sea_Horse_(1855).jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/William-Adolphe_Bouguereau","/wiki/File:Arion_poet_riding_a_dolphin_circa_1514_D%C3%BCrer.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5e/Arion_poet_riding_a_dolphin_circa_1514_D%C3%BCrer.jpg/240px-Arion_poet_riding_a_dolphin_circa_1514_D%C3%BCrer.jpg","/wiki/File:Arion_poet_riding_a_dolphin_circa_1514_D%C3%BCrer.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/Albrecht_D%C3%BCrer","/wiki/Ancient_Greek","/wiki/Kitharode","/wiki/Ancient_Greece","/wiki/Dionysus","